Made in Rwanda Content Recommender
A CPU-friendly content-based recommender for the AIMS KTT Hackathon challenge S2.T1.3. The system uses TF-IDF over product metadata, cosine similarity for retrieval, a local-boost rule for Made-in-Rwanda items, and a curated fallback when no strong local substitute is found.

Project files
recommender.py — main retrieval pipeline and CLI.

eval.ipynb — notebook for evaluation with NDCG@5 and local-presence rate.

dispatcher.md — product and business adaptation artifact.

process_log.md — hour-by-hour work log and declared LLM/tool use.

SIGNED.md — signed honor code.

Expected data
Place the CSV files in data/:

data/catalog.csv

data/queries.csv

data/click_log.csv (optional but recommended)

Required columns in catalog.csv are:
sku, title, description, category, material, origin_district, price_rwf, artisan_id.

Quick start
bash
pip install pandas numpy scikit-learn scipy jupyter
python recommender.py --q "leather boots"
Example command
bash
python recommender.py --q "cadeau en cuir pour femme" --top_k 5
Method summary
Build a TF-IDF representation from concatenated product text.

Compute cosine similarity between query text and product text.

Apply a local boost to local items.

Add a small popularity prior from click logs.

Trigger curated fallback if the top global match is non-local and no local item passes the similarity threshold.

Notes
This baseline is designed for CPU-only use and small catalog size, which fits the challenge constraints.

You should report final NDCG@5 and local-presence rate from eval.ipynb in the README and in your video intro.

