## 3. Three representative prompts I actually used

### Prompt 1 — Specification understanding and plan

> *“Here is the S2.T1.3 Made in Rwanda Content Recommender brief. Help me extract the exact technical and product deliverables and propose a simple Python-based TF-IDF recommender design that fits CPU-only and low-tech constraints.”*

### Prompt 2 — Baseline code scaffolding

> *“Python is OK. I will create catalog.csv, queries.csv, and click_log.csv under data/. Please write a recommender.py with TF-IDF + cosine similarity + local boost + curated fallback, and a CLI ‘python recommender.py --q \"leather boots\"’.”*

### Prompt 3 — Evaluation & metrics

> *“Given recommender.py, draft an eval.ipynb that loads catalog.csv, queries.csv, and click_log.csv, builds relevance labels from clicks and global best match, and computes NDCG@5 and local-presence rate for all queries.”*

---

## 4. One prompt I considered but discarded — and why

> *“Generate a very complex deep-learning-based multilingual sentence embedding recommender with transformers and GPU acceleration.”*

**Why I discarded it:**  
I realised this would violate the spirit and constraints of the challenge (CPU-only, no paid APIs, and Tier 1 emphasis on clarity over deep ML). A transformer-based approach would add complexity and latency without clear benefit for a 400-product catalog, and I might not be able to fully defend it in the live defence. I chose a TF-IDF baseline with clear trade-offs instead.[file:2][file:1]

---

## 5. Hardest decision and how I resolved it

The hardest decision was **choosing TF-IDF + cosine similarity over multilingual sentence embeddings** for query–product matching.

- **Arguments for sentence embeddings:**
  - Better handling of French / English / code-switched queries in principle.
  - Potentially more robust to spelling variants.

- **Arguments for TF-IDF:**
  - Fits the CPU-only, no-paid-API constraints perfectly.[file:2]
  - Very fast on a 400-item catalog and simple to optimise.
  - Easy to explain in the 4-minute video and in the live defence: bag-of-words, cosine similarity, and a simple local boost.
  - Relevance can be improved by careful tokenisation and n‑grams on product metadata without introducing heavy dependencies.

I ultimately chose **TF-IDF with bigrams + a local-boost rule + a small popularity prior** as a baseline that is:
- Transparent and reproducible,
- Easy to reason about when explaining NDCG@5 and local-presence rate,
- And aligned with the tier and constraints of the challenge.

If I had more time or a higher-tier challenge, I would consider adding a plug‑in sentence embedding model as a secondary candidate generator, but the baseline here remains deliberately simple and defensible.
